UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 343/GA
1 AN ACT relating to the Department of Workers' Claims and declaring an
2 emergency.
3 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
4 SECTION 1. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 342 IS CREATED TO
5 READ AS FOLLOWS:
6 (1) There is hereby created the Department of Workers' Claims administratively
7 attached to the Office of the Governor, which shall be headed by a commissioner
8 appointed by the Governor and confirmed by the Senate in accordance with
9 Section 6 of this Act.
10 (2) The department shall be divided for administrative purposes into the:
11 (a) Office of the Commissioner;
12 (b) Office of General Counsel:
13 (c) Office of Administrative Law Judges;
14 (d) Division of Claims Processing;
15 (e) Division of Security and Compliance;
16 (f) Division of Workers' Compensation Funds; and
17 (g) Division of Specialist and Medical Services.
18 (3) The Office of Administrative Law Judges shall be headed by a chief
19 administrative law judge appointed in accordance with Section 7 of this Act.
20 (4) Each division in the department shall be headed by a director appointed by the
21 commissioner with the approval of the Governor in accordance with KRS 12.050.
22 (5) The Workers' Compensation Board shall be attached to the Department of
23 Workers' Claims for administrative purposes only.
24 Section 2. KRS 342.0011 is amended to read as follows:
25 As used in this chapter, unless the context otherwise requires:
26 (1) "Injury" means any work-related traumatic event or series of traumatic events,
27 including cumulative trauma, arising out of and in the course of employment which
Page 1 of 58
SB034310.100 - 1402 - XXXX 3/10/2026 3:36 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 343/GA
1 is the proximate cause producing a harmful change in the human organism
2 evidenced by objective medical findings. "Injury" does not include the effects of the
3 natural aging process, and does not include any communicable disease unless the
4 risk of contracting the disease is increased by the nature of the employment.
5 "Injury" when used generally, unless the context indicates otherwise, shall include
6 an occupational disease and damage to a prosthetic appliance, but shall not include
7 a psychological, psychiatric, or stress-related change in the human organism, unless
8 it is a direct result of a physical injury;
9 (2) "Occupational disease" means a disease arising out of and in the course of the
10 employment;
11 (3) An occupational disease as defined in this chapter shall be deemed to arise out of
12 the employment if there is apparent to the rational mind, upon consideration of all
13 the circumstances, a causal connection between the conditions under which the
14 work is performed and the occupational disease, and which can be seen to have
15 followed as a natural incident to the work as a result of the exposure occasioned by
16 the nature of the employment and which can be fairly traced to the employment as
17 the proximate cause. The occupational disease shall be incidental to the character of
18 the business and not independent of the relationship of employer and employee. An
19 occupational disease need not have been foreseen or expected but, after its
20 contraction, it must appear to be related to a risk connected with the employment
21 and to have flowed from that source as a rational consequence;
22 (4) "Injurious exposure" shall mean that exposure to occupational hazard which would,
23 independently of any other cause whatsoever, produce or cause the disease for
24 which the claim is made;
25 (5) "Death" means death resulting from an injury or occupational disease;
26 (6) "Carrier" means any insurer, or legal representative thereof, authorized to insure the
27 liability of employers under this chapter and includes a self-insurer;
Page 2 of 58
