12 Section 14. KRS 218A.278 is amended to read as follows:
13 (1) As used in[For the purposes of] this section:
14 (a) "Analyze" means to apply scientific and mathematical measures to determine
15 meaningful patterns and associations in data. "Analyze" includes descriptive
16 analysis to examine historical data, predictive analysis to examine future
17 probabilities and trends, and prescriptive analysis to examine how future
18 decisions may impact the population and trends; and
19 (b) "Pilot program" means a program in a county or set of counties, or a subset or
20 subsets of the population, as designated by the Cabinet for Health and Family
21 Services and the Office of Drug Control Policy for analyzing the effectiveness
22 of substance abuse treatment services in Kentucky.
23 (2) The general purpose of this section is to assist in the development of a pilot
24 program to analyze the outcomes and effectiveness of substance abuse treatment
25 programs in order to ensure that the Commonwealth is:
26 (a) Addressing appropriate risk and protective factors for substance abuse in a
27 defined population;
Page 52 of 58
SB034310.100 - 1402 - XXXX 3/10/2026 3:36 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 343/GA
1 (b) Using approaches that have been shown to be effective;
2 (c) Intervening early at important stages and transitions;
3 (d) Intervening in appropriate settings and domains; and
4 (e) Managing programs effectively.
5 (3) Sources of data for the pilot program shall include, at a minimum, claims under the
6 Kentucky Department for Medicaid Services, the electronic monitoring system for
7 controlled substances established under KRS 218A.202, and the Department of
8 Workers' Claims[ within the Education and Labor Cabinet].
9 (4) As funds are available, the Cabinet for Health and Family Services and the Office
10 of Drug Control Policy shall initiate a pilot program to determine, collect, and
11 analyze performance measurement data for substance abuse treatment services to
12 determine practices that reduce frequency of relapse, provide better outcomes for
13 patients, hold patients accountable, and control health costs related to substance
14 abuse.
15 (5) By December 31, 2016, the Cabinet for Health and Family Services and the Office
16 of Drug Control Policy shall issue a joint report to the Legislative Research
17 Commission and the Office of the Governor that:
18 (a) Details the findings of the pilot program;
19 (b) Includes recommendations based on the pilot program's results for optimizing
20 substance abuse treatment services; and
21 (c) Includes recommendations for the continued application of analytics to further
22 augment Kentucky's approach to fighting substance abuse in the future.
